<paragraph id="011C36F6FFCAFFF9F9D9AADEF469FF2D" blockId="2.[151,595,173,239]" box="[151,529,213,239]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
<heading id="5A54819AFFCAFFF9F9D9AADEF469FF2D" bold="true" box="[151,529,213,239]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" reason="1">
<taxonomicName id="C6A34D75FFCAFFF9F9D9AADEF469FF2D" authority="Bishop &amp; Crosby 1938" authorityName="Bishop &amp; Crosby" authorityYear="1938" box="[151,529,213,239]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Scirites" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33D7EAE4FFCAFFF9F9D9AADEF469FF2D" bold="true" box="[151,529,213,239]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis id="33D7EAE4FFCAFFF9F9D9AADEF689FF2D" bold="true" box="[151,241,213,239]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Scirites</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="65324B07FFCAFFF9F9B6AADEF469FF2D" author="Bishop" box="[248,529,213,239]" pageId="2" pageNumber="57" refString="Bishop, S. C. &amp; Crosby, C. R. (1938) Studies in American spiders: miscellaneous genera of Erigoninae, part II. Journal of the New York Entomological Society 46 (1), 55 - 107." type="journal article" year="1938">
Bishop &amp; Crosby 
<number id="B76B24D1FFCAFFF9F899AADEF469FF2D" box="[471,529,213,239]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1938.0">1938</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="011C36F6FFCAFFF9F9D9AB13F521FD88" blockId="2.[151,1437,280,1146]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
In their characterization of this North American genus, 
<bibRefCitation id="65324B07FFCAFFF9FA77AB13F21EFEF0" author="Bishop" box="[825,1126,280,306]" pageId="2" pageNumber="57" refString="Bishop, S. C. &amp; Crosby, C. R. (1938) Studies in American spiders: miscellaneous genera of Erigoninae, part II. Journal of the New York Entomological Society 46 (1), 55 - 107." type="journal article" year="1938">
Bishop &amp; Crosby (
<number id="B76B24D1FFCAFFF9FD6EAB13F225FEF0" box="[1056,1117,280,306]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1938.0">1938</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
mention that it is closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="C6A34D75FFCAFFF9F843AB4BF4AEFE98" authority="Bishop &amp; Crosby 1938" authorityName="Bishop &amp; Crosby" authorityYear="1938" box="[269,726,320,346]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Scolopembolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33D7EAE4FFCAFFF9F843AB4BF7C6FE9B" box="[269,446,320,345]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Scolopembolus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="65324B07FFCAFFF9F888AB4BF4AEFE98" author="Bishop" box="[454,726,320,346]" pageId="2" pageNumber="57" refString="Bishop, S. C. &amp; Crosby, C. R. (1938) Studies in American spiders: miscellaneous genera of Erigoninae, part II. Journal of the New York Entomological Society 46 (1), 55 - 107." type="journal article" year="1938">
Bishop &amp; Crosby 
<number id="B76B24D1FFCAFFF9FBD5AB4BF4AEFE98" box="[667,726,320,346]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1938.0">1938</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
having the same 
<typeStatus id="DE188854FFCAFFF9FAEBAB4BF5AFFE98" box="[933,983,320,346]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">type</typeStatus>
of embolic division, but differs by the male palpal tibia and by the anterior metatarsi bearing a row of long curved spines. In the present paper, we did not support nor reject this hypothesis, but we suspect that this relationship is valid based on superficial morphology. We were however able to establish close relationship with 
<taxonomicName id="C6A34D75FFCAFFF9FAA5ABB3F374FE10" authority="Simon 1884" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1884" box="[1003,1292,440,466]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Tapinocyba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33D7EAE4FFCAFFF9FAA5ABB3F20BFE13" box="[1003,1139,440,465]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Tapinocyba</emphasis>
Simon 
<number id="B76B24D1FFCAFFF9FD81ABB3F374FE10" box="[1231,1292,440,466]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1884.0">1884</number>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="C6A34D75FFCAFFF9FC54ABB3F75FFE38" authority="Banks 1905" authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1905" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Ceratinops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33D7EAE4FFCAFFF9FC54ABB3F3E5FE13" box="[1306,1437,440,465]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Ceratinops</emphasis>
Banks 
<number id="B76B24D1FFCAFFF9F9A2ABEBF75FFE38" box="[236,295,480,506]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1905.0">1905</number>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="C6A34D75FFCAFFF9F826ABEBF480FE38" authority="Wunderlich 1992" authorityName="Wunderlich" authorityYear="1992" box="[360,760,480,506]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Parapelecopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33D7EAE4FFCAFFF9F826ABEBF465FE3B" box="[360,541,480,505]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Parapelecopsis</emphasis>
Wunderlich 
<number id="B76B24D1FFCAFFF9FBF3ABEBF480FE38" box="[701,760,480,506]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1992.0">1992</number>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="C6A34D75FFCAFFF9FA45ABEBF51BFE3B" box="[779,867,480,505]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Scirites" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33D7EAE4FFCAFFF9FA45ABEBF51BFE3B" box="[779,867,480,505]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Scirites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is now composed of two species, both distinguished by a rather simple embolic division, the absence of embolic membrane, and the presence of a distinct row of 
<number id="B76B24D1FFCAFFF9F9A2A83BF682FD88" box="[236,250,560,586]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="7.0">7</number>
curved megaspines on the metatarsus I of the male.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="49B9657DFFCAFFF9F988A85CF4DCFCD0" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="011C36F6FFCAFFF9F988A85CF4DCFCD0" blockId="2.[151,1437,280,1146]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis id="33D7EAE4FFCAFFF9F988A85CF71CFDB3" bold="true" box="[198,356,599,625]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Diagnosis.—</emphasis>
Males of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="C6A34D75FFCAFFF9FB09A853F4E7FDB3" box="[583,671,600,625]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Scirites" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33D7EAE4FFCAFFF9FB09A853F4E7FDB3" box="[583,671,600,625]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Scirites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differ from all other erigonines by the presence of a row of seven curved megaspines on metatarsus I. Females show no clear characters allowing differentiation from most erigonines, particularly from the North American genera 
<taxonomicName id="C6A34D75FFCAFFF9FA7CA8A3F5C2FD03" box="[818,954,680,705]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Tapinocyba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33D7EAE4FFCAFFF9FA7CA8A3F5C2FD03" box="[818,954,680,705]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Tapinocyba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="C6A34D75FFCAFFF9FD4FA8A3F3E0FD00" authority="Bishop &amp; Crosby 1935" authorityName="Bishop &amp; Crosby" authorityYear="1935" box="[1025,1432,680,706]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Cheniseo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33D7EAE4FFCAFFF9FD4FA8A3F216FD03" box="[1025,1134,680,705]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Cheniseo</emphasis>
Bishop &amp; Crosby 
<number id="B76B24D1FFCAFFF9FC14A8A3F3E0FD00" box="[1370,1432,680,706]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1935.0">1935</number>
</taxonomicName>
. They however differ from the closely related 
<taxonomicName id="C6A34D75FFCAFFF9FBE1A8DBF54AFD2B" box="[687,818,720,745]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Ceratinops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33D7EAE4FFCAFFF9FBE1A8DBF54AFD2B" box="[687,818,720,745]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Ceratinops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the longitudinal opening of the ventral plate (see 
<bibRefCitation id="65324B07FFCAFFF9F9D9A8F3F7CAFCD0" author="Paquin" box="[151,434,760,786]" pageId="2" pageNumber="58" refString="Paquin, P. &amp; Duperre, N. (2003) Guide d'identification des araignees (Araneae) du Quebec. Fabreries, Supplement 11, 251 pp." type="book" year="2003">
Paquin &amp; Dupérré 
<number id="B76B24D1FFCAFFF9F83BA8F3F7CAFCD0" box="[373,434,760,786]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="2003.0">2003</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, figs 
<number id="B76B24D1FFCAFFF9F8BFA8F3F4E0FCD0" box="[497,664,760,786]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="8.58862866E8">858, 862, 866</number>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="49B9657DFFCAFFF9F988A914F35FFBB8" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" type="description">
<paragraph id="011C36F6FFCAFFF9F988A914F35FFBB8" blockId="2.[151,1437,280,1146]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis id="33D7EAE4FFCAFFF9F988A914F704FCFB" bold="true" box="[198,380,799,825]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Description.—</emphasis>
Small spiders (~ 
<number id="B76B24D1FFCAFFF9FB09A92BF4C6FCF8" box="[583,702,800,826]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1.315" valueMax="1.49" valueMin="1.14">1.14–1.49</number>
) with the following characters: Tm I 
<number id="B76B24D1FFCAFFF9FD3FA92BF291FCF8" box="[1137,1257,800,826]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="0.5700000000000001" valueMax="0.62" valueMin="0.52">0.52–0.62</number>
, Tm IV absent, tibial spination 
<number id="B76B24D1FFCAFFF9F81DA943F71AFCA0" box="[339,354,840,866]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1.0">1</number>
<number id="B76B24D1FFCAFFF9F822A943F703FCA0" box="[364,379,840,866]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1.0">1</number>
<number id="B76B24D1FFCAFFF9F8CBA943F7ECFCA0" box="[389,404,840,866]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1.0">1</number>
<number id="B76B24D1FFCAFFF9F8D1A943F7D7FCA0" box="[415,431,840,866]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1.0">1</number>
. Median tracheal trunk branched into bundles of small tracheoles without taenidia. Presence of 
<number id="B76B24D1FFCAFFF9F862A97BF743FC48" box="[300,315,880,906]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="7.0">7</number>
curved megaspines on metatarsus I of male (
<figureCitation id="99982A73FFCAFFF9FA2BA97BF5D5FC48" box="[869,941,880,906]" captionStart="FIGURES 1" captionStartId="4.[151,269,1759,1783]" captionTargetBox="[164,1417,355,1740]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[157,1429,352,1752]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1. Scirites. 1, male metatarsus I, lateral view; 2 – 9 Scirites pectinatus 2, male cephalothorax, lateral view, 3, palpus of male, ventral view, 4, expanded male palpus, schematic lateral view, 5, palpus of male, lateral view, 6, palpal tibia of male, dorsal view, 7, epigynum, ventral view, 8, spermathecae, ventral view, 9, spermathecae, dorsal view. 1 – 3, 5 scale bar = 0.1; 4, 6 – 9 scale bar = 0.05. CD copulatory ducts; DP dorsal plate; DSA distal suprategular apophysis; E embolus; FD fertilization ducts; F fundus; MSA marginal suprategular apophysis; P paracymbium; PT protegulum; PTP protegular papillae; PTA pedipalpal tibial apophysis; R radix; S spermathecae; SPT suprategulum; T tegulum; TP tailpiece; VP ventral plate." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/176407/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
Fig. 
<number id="B76B24D1FFCAFFF9FAD1A97BF5D5FC48" box="[927,941,880,906]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). The male carapace is raised in the eye region and somewhat flat (Figs 2, 10). Male palp with a rather simple embolic division consisting of a tailpiece, radix and embolus (Figs 3, 4, 11, 12). Tegulum rather large in ventral view, protegulum large and bearing protegular papillae (Figs 3, 11). Distal suprategular apophysis basal part sclerotized changing to membranous, with or without marginal suprategular apophysis (Figs 4, 12). Paracymbium variable (Figs 5, 13). Palpal tibia variable (Figs 6, 14). Female epigynal plate somewhat rectangular, spermathecae rounded, well separated, situated each side of the junction of ventral plate and dorsal plate (Figs 7, 8, 15, 16).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
